Evolution of (a) the asymptotic Vt and (b) the shift Vtasympt – Vtstart as a function of the CG biasing voltage (I = 48.4 GW/cm2) for initially erased and initially programmed cells.

The simulation of the electrical behaviour of the initially erased and programmed Flash cells show that, in both cases, the band diagram of the tunnel capacitor can be “flattened” when the VCG values extracted from Fig. 8b are applied on the control gate. The threshold voltage remains constant because no net charge transit is possible through the tunnel oxide as the band diagram is flat, in accordance with19. Under the hypothesis that the Vtasympt is reached when the band diagram of the tunnel capacitor becomes flat, which has been demonstrated through the results presented in this section of the report, and considering the drain, source and bulk terminals to be grounded (VD = VS = VB = 0 V), we were able to derive in one of our previous works19 the following relationship:10\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
